<div class="markdown"><h4>Data Science Applications to Astronomy</h4><h1>Week 4: Model Building II:</h1><h2>Model Assessment</h2></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Overview of Workflow for Assessing Models</h2><ol><li><p>Validate methods using simulated data</p></li><li><p>Validate computation</p></li><li><p>Compare Likelihood to expected distribution</p></li><li><p>Sensitivity to individual data points</p></li><li><p>Sensitivity to assumptions (e.g., prior distributions)</p></li><li><p>Check Predictive distribution</p></li><li><p>Cross validation</p></li></ol></div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Step 1: Validate methods using simulated data</h1><ul><li><p>Generate simulated data sets that satisfy all model assumptions.  </p></li><li><p>Apply model and computational methods to simulated data</p></li><li><p>Compare results to true parameter values.</p></li></ul><h2>Checks to perform based on simulated data:</h2><ul><li><p>Are estimated model parameters close to true values?</p></li><li><p>Do estimated parameter uncertainties accurately characterize the dispersion from the true values?</p></li><li><p>Is the distribution of parameter estimates centered on their true values?</p></li><li><p>How many iterations are required for algorithms to converge?  </p></li><li><p>What can we learn reliably?    </p></li><li><p>Are there regions of parameter space that result in low quality inference?</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h4>Validating methods on simulated data is a key step <br/> (too often overlooked)</h4><p>This approach is very useful for diagnosing many of the most common problems:</p><ul><li><p>Not enough data</p></li><li><p>Measurement uncertainties too large</p></li><li><p>Spatial or temporal sampling leads to degeneracies</p></li><li><p>Model has too many unknown parameters</p></li><li><p>Iterative algorithms don't converge reliably</p></li><li><p>Iterative algorithms take longer than expected to converge</p></li></ul><p>Real data is (almost always) more complicated than our idealizd model, but...  </p><ul><li><p>If our method doesn't work reliabily for idealized data, then we shouldn't trust the outputs when they are applied to real data.</p></li><li><p>If our method requires <span class="tex">\(10^6\)</span> iterations to converge for idealized data, then we know we'll need to run it for at least that long for real data (and potentially longer).</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Step 2: Validate the computation</h1><p>(This step applies regardless of whether analyzing simulated or real data.)</p><ul><li><p>Are the results pausible?</p><ul><li><p>E.g., Magnitude of best-fit value for each model parameter</p></li></ul></li><li><p>For algorithms that have stochastic element, are results robust to:</p><ul><li><p>Different (reasonable) initial guesses?</p></li><li><p>Different draws from psuedo-random number generator?</p></li></ul></li><li><p>For itterative algorithms:</p><ul><li><p>Why did algorithm stop?</p></li><li><p>Any warning signs of non-convergence?</p></li></ul></li><li><p>For algorithms that return an uncertainty estimate, is the reported precission:</p><ul><li><p>Robust?</p></li><li><p>Scientifically useful?</p></li></ul></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Step 3: Compare Likelihood to expected distribution</h1><p>Likelihood: </p><p class="tex">$$\begin{eqnarray}
\mathcal{L} &amp; = &amp; p( \mathrm{data} \; | \; \mathrm{model\; parameters}, \; \mathrm{model} ) \\
&amp; = &amp; p (y|θ,M) = p(y|\theta)
\end{eqnarray}$$</p><p>Often, we have a complex <em>physical model</em>, but a relatively simple model of the <em>measurement process</em>.  In these cases, if we knew the full model was correct and the model parameters (<span class="tex">\(\theta\)</span>), then we can compute the distribution of the likelihood. </p><p>For simple measurement models, this can often be done analytically.  E.g., </p><ul><li><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution">Poisson distribution</a> for sum of counts (if counts are from a Poisson process)</p></li><li><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chi-squared_distribution">χ² distribution</a> for sum of squared residuals (if measurement errors are Gaussian)</p></li><li><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-distribution"><em>F</em>-distribution</a> for ratio of two variables drawn from χ² distribution</p></li></ul><p>For more complex measurement models, this is often done via simulation.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Step 4: Inspect Sensitivity to individual data points</h1><p>In practice, there are usually complications omitted from the model being used for inference. </p><ul><li><p>Could be missing astrophysics (e.g., sample of targets is contaminated with a small fraction of objects that different from intended sample)</p></li><li><p>Could be incomplete model for measurement process (e.g., cosmic ray, observer points telescope at wrong object, ...)</p></li></ul><p>To procted against making poor decissions/scientific inferences:</p><ul><li><p>Ask would our decisions/inferences change if a small fraction of measurements had be omitted from analysis?  </p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Step 5: Sensitivity to prior distribution/assumptions</h1><ul><li><p>In a Bayesian analysis, we specify prior assumptions quantitatively by specifying a prior distribution for unknown model parameters.</p></li><li><p>There are assumptions in any model (even if they're hard to find, e.g., in a frequentist test). </p></li><li><p>Usually, reasonable scientists could make different reasonable assumptions.  </p></li><li><p>The precise quantiative results will differ depending on the assumptions.</p></li><li><p>The differences in the results under different assumptions might be:</p><ul><li><p>So small they are scientifically unininteresting,</p></li><li><p>So large that more detailed analysis isn't a good use of your time,</p></li><li><p>Somewhere in the middle.  </p></li></ul></li><li><p>We need to know where this analysis falls along that spectrum <em>before</em> we start drawing scientific conclusions.</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Step 6: Check posterior predictive distribution</h1><ul><li><p>Does model make good "predictions" for the observed data?</p></li></ul></div>

<div class="markdown"><h1>Step 7: Perform Cross validation</h1><ul><li><p>Previously, we fit a model based on all of our observations and then asked if the resulting model made good <strong>"postdictions"</strong>.  This is a relatively weak test.</p></li><li><p>A stronger test would be to see if the model can make good <strong>predictions</strong> for new data.  </p></li><li><p>Often, acquiring new data is very time consuming/expensive.</p></li><li><p>This motivates a more powerful method for assessing models: <strong>cross validation (CV)</strong>.</p></li></ul><h2>Cross validation of a single model</h2><ul><li><p>Divide data into <strong>two subsets</strong> (e.g., 75% "training", 25% "validation")</p></li><li><p>Fit data ("train model") using only the <strong>training set</strong></p></li><li><p>Use resulting parameters to make predictions for <strong>validation set</strong></p></li><li><p>How well did the model do?  (evaluate "loss function")</p></li></ul><h2>Cross validation when considering multiple models</h2><ul><li><p>Divide data into <strong>three subsets</strong> (e.g., 60% "training", 20% "validation", 20% "test")</p></li><li><p>For each model you want to consider:</p><ul><li><p>Fit/Train using only data from training set</p></li><li><p>Validate using only data from validation set</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Pick which model you'll use for decissions/publication:</p></li><li><p>Evaluate predictions for <strong>test set</strong>.</p></li><li><p>Report results on test data.</p></li><li><p><strong>Avoid temptation</strong> to make further "improvements" at the point.</p></li></ul></div>

<div class="markdown"><h2>Priors</h2></div>


<div class="markdown"><div class="admonition is-question"><header class="admonition-header">Question:</header><div class="admonition-body"><p>Is prior and posterior the same thing?</p></div></div></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Both are PDFs.  But in any given analysis (with non-zero data), they are different functions:</p><p class="tex">$$\mathrm{(Posterior)} = \mathrm{(Prior)} \times \mathrm{(Likelihood)} / \mathrm{(Evidence)}$$</p><p class="tex">$$p( \theta| M, D) = \frac{p(\theta | M) p(D | \theta, M )}{p(D | M )}$$</p></div>
